postcontent:
Very good condition.  SN 5843XXX.  I say appears to be parts correct because I don't know enough about the small parts to say for sure they are correct.  I will list the main parts and numbers below.  These have been verified to be correct.  Also, it sits in a genuine GI stock.  The stock has the correct circle (P) on the stock as well as the RIA EB cartouche.  It also has the Raritan Armory (RA) cartouche from New Jersey.  Anybody who knows about M1's, knows the RIA EB stamp means Rock Island Armory Elmer Bjorke.  Bjorke was the head armorer for Rock Island until 1958.  I guessing it was re-arsenaled twice.  Once by Elmer before 58 and again in the early 60's by RA.  

The SN puts the manafacture date around 1955.

title: For Sale:  Mauser Modelo Argentino 1891   sale or trade
postcontent:
I have a nice Argentinian Mauser made in Berlin Germany. Receiver is marked "Mauser Modelo Argentino 1891, Manufactura Loewe Berlin". Caliber 7.65x53, All matching number on the receiver, barrel, bolt handle, and trigger guard. I believe this is the Calvary model with the shorter barrel and stock, total length is 37" barrel is 18" ish. Ammo is still available for these 120+ year old rifles and it runs less than $20 a box for PPU brand. These rifles do not require an FFL to buy or sell since they are pre-1899 production and are classed as Antiques by the ATF - see: 18 USC 921 (a)(16). Since these rifles can shoot modern ammunition and are also exempt from FFL transfers they do bring a slight premium and typically sell for $400-$800 on Gunbroker depending on if the numbers all match, if the Argentine Crest was removed or not, and the rifles overall condition. This one has all matching numbers and the Argentine Crest was not removed which makes it more desirable. The condition however is fair; most of the bluing is gone and there is some pitting, the bore however is nice and bright and the rifling clear but worn as expected for its age. Very unique collectable and like most Mausers, they continue to gain value year after year. 

Willing to trade for a modern firearm in a common caliber, prefer stainless, +/- cash as needed, or I will consider reasonable cash offers, lowballers will be ignored.

Must be willing to meet near I-25 and Longmont, private party paperless trades / sale only. No bill of sale required, but must be Colorado resident not prohibited from owning a firearm.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Tec 9, With all accessories, (PRE-BAN GUN)
postcontent:
THIS IS A PRE BAN GUN, AND MY FATHER WAS THE ONLY OWNER. HE BOUGHT IT AT A GUN SHOW IN 1981, WE FIRED A BOX OF 50 ROUNDS THROUGH IT, CLEANED IT AND DISPLAYED IT. UNTIL NOW, IT GOES UP FOR SALE OR TRADE.
 LIKE NEW CONDITION, WITH (4) 32 ROUND MAGS, FLASH SUPPRESSOR, FOREND PISTOL GRIP, FACTORY CUSTOM CASE, AND EVEN OWNERS MANUAL.
 KEEP IN MIND, DUE TO THIS BEING A PRE BAN GUN, THESE EXTRAS WERE ILLEGAL FOR THIS GUN AT ONE POINT, AND I AM PRETTY SURE IT WILL HAPPEN AGAIN IN THE VERY NEAR FUTURE, GET IT NOW AND YOU WILL BE GRANDFATHERED IN.
 PRICE $1,000.00 CASH OR TRADE ON AN H&K PISTOL
 CALL OR TEXT 865-660-8491 
HAVE PICTURES ON PHONE TO TEXT
 ALSO PLEASE KEEP IN MIND, WHEN YOU ARE SEARCHING FOR INFORMATION ON THIS WEAPON, IT IS NO LONGER PRODUCED, AND THIS IS THE ORGINAL MODEL, NOT ONE THAT WAS ALTERED BY THE COMPANY TO TRY AND MEET POST BAN ACCEPTANCE.

 SINCE I HAVE HAD NUMEROUR QUESTIONS ABOUT THE “PRE-BAN” HERE IS A LITTLE INFORMATION I HOPE HELPS EVERYONE TO UNDERSTAND BETTER

 The TEC-9 and, eventually, TEC-DC9 variants were listed among the 19 firearms banned by name in the USA by the now expired 1994 Federal Assault Weapons Ban (AWB).[1] This ban caused the cessation of their manufacture, and forced Intratec to introduce a newer model called the AB-10, a TEC-9 Mini without a threaded muzzle/barrel shroud and limited to a 10 round magazine instead of a 20 or 32 round magazine. However, it accepted the high capacity magazines of the pre-ban models.
 The Federal Assault Weapons Ban (AWB), or Public Safety and Recreational Firearms Use Protection Act, was a subtitle of the Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act of 1994, a federal law in the United States that included a prohibition on the manufacture for civilian use of certain semi-automatic firearms, so called "assault weapons".[1] The 10-year ban was passed by Congress on September 13, 1994, and was signed into law by President Bill Clinton the same day. The ban only applied to weapons manufactured after the date of the ban's enactment.
 In the former U.S. law, the legal term assault weapon included certain specific semi-automatic firearm models by name (e.g., Colt AR-15, TEC-9, non-select-fire AK-47s produced by three manufacturers, and Uzis) and other semi-automatic firearms because they possess a minimum set of cosmetic features from the following list of features below:
• Pistol Grip (Tec 9 has)
• For end Grip (Tec9 has)
• Flash Suppressor (Tec9 has)
• Grenade Launcher (does not have)
• Magazine that attached outside of the grip (Tec9 has)
• Folding stock (does not have)
• Bayonet Mount (does not have)
 During this ban, your weapon was legal with only 2(TWO) of the accessories. As you can see this PRE-BAN weapon has 4!!!!!

 II. The Tec-9 Is A Semi-Automatic Version Of A Military Submachinegun

The TEC-9 is a semi-automatic version of a military submachinegun. Although it has been marketed under various names -- the KG-9, the KG-99, the TEC-9, and the TEC-DC9 -- and by various companies owned and operated by the Garcia family, the basic design of the weapon has remained virtually unchanged. The company decided to manufacture the KG-9 because of the growing market for military style guns in the United States. The KG-9's manual described it as: 
Combining the high capacity and controlled firepower of the military submachinegun with the legal status and light weight of a handgun.The term "assault pistol" was coined by the firearms industry to describe the KG-9 was an illegal machine gun, due to the ease with which it could be converted to fully automatic fire.


A. The KG-9 Was Banned as a Machine Gun, and Renamed the KG-99

In 1982, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms ruled that the KG-9 was an illegal machine gun, due to the ease with which it could be converted to fully automatic fire.

The company redesigned the KG-9's bolt to make conversion more difficult, and renamed the weapon the KG-99. Otherwise, the design remained essentially unchanged. Intratec confirmed that like its predecessor, the KG-99 could be fairly described as "combining the high capacity and controlled firepower of the military submachinegun with the legal status and light weight of a handgun."

Intratec U.S.A. ("Intratec") manufactured a vertical foregrip for use with the KG-99, which it marketed as an "Assault Grip." Intratec used the term "Assault Grip" in marketing the foregrip, "[b]ecause you basically hold the gun with two hands like you would as assault weapon, a military weapon."

In November 1982, and again in March 1985, the ATF notified Intratec that it was unlawful to possess a KG-99 and an attachable foregrip, even though the pistol and the foregrip were disassembled. Although Intratec understood that they should not be selling the assault grip, he continued to sell it as an accessory for the KG-99, stamping on the order form that "ATF has ruled that the KG-250 assault grip may not be attached legally to the KG-99 or the old model KG-9."

B. Intratec Rename the KG-99 the TEC-9, and Continued to Sell the "Assault Grip."

Intratec renamed the KG-99 the TEC in August 1985. The TEC-9 was substantially identical to the KG-99, with just a few cosmetic changes. The company resumed marketing the assault grip without any warning, advertising that it "Attaches to All TEC-9" Intratec advertised the TEC-9 as a "High-spirited" weapon that is "as tough as your toughest customer." The company’s brochure emphasized the weapon’s "paramilitary" appeal, its "Military blowback design," and its "Combat-type" sights. The brochure depicted a smoking target of a human being shot dozens of times through the head and the heart in what appears to be a fusillade of automatic weapons fire. In April 1987, Intratec was sued by the Estate of David Bengston in Connecticut state court. The complaint alleged that the decedent, a school custodian, was fatally shot in the head with a TEC-9M ["Mini"], and that Intratec "knew or should have known that the TEC-9M gun was and is primarily suited for an/or used in criminal activity," and that it "lacks legitimate use, such as sporting, law enforcement of self-protection." In November 1987, Carlos Garcia formed Navegar in order to take the assets of the business back from his father and avoid Intratec’s liabilities. Navegar continued to manufacture and market the TEC-9, and continued to do business as Intratec. Intratec U.S.A. declared bankruptcy in 1989, with the Bengston and Alicki lawsuits as its only significant liabilities.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Mini-30 + lots of goodies
location: Westchester County, Hudson Valley, New York
postcontent:
I've got a Ruger Mini-30 7.62x39 semi-automatic rifle. It's just like a Mini 14, except it shoots the AK round instead of the AR round.

It's got the regular, NEW YORK LEGAL wood stock, void of a collapsible butt stock or a pistol grip, meaning the commie lawmakers won't call it an "assault weapon." This guy is just about as good as it gets in New York. It's a hell of a rifle, light and handy, but powerful enough to blast your way through a cinder block wall. If you've never seen one, it looks and comes apart like an M1 Carbine, but it shoots like an AK-47. I've put high quality American Winchester ammo through it, and I've put cheap Golden Tiger and Tula surplus ammo through it, and it eats it up. Steel cased ammo is no problem.

In addition, I also have a black ATI tactical stock. This item is a black stock built for the Mini 14, except I used a dremel to widen the magazine well to accommodate the Mini 30 magazines. It could use some smoothing down, but it works just fine. This stock has a pistol grip and telescoping stock, as well as side and top rails. The item must be sold SEPARATELY seeing as, once it is placed on the rifle, it makes the rifle become an "assault weapon." I would like to stress this again. This item is to be sold separately. It is included in the price but needs to be paid for and shipped separately.

In addition to the extra stock, I have an Accu-Strut put on, and a 4x scope with its own rail. The scope rail is to be mounted on the rifle's sights. I have never mounted it as I am not much of a scope guy. I also have a flash suppressor, but unfortunately, the commies in New York don't think you should be able to have one, so it's not for sale. I'll have to get rid of it somehow else.

The rifle comes with a 5-round Ruger magazine that's only been used once or twice, and two 10-round aftermarket magazines that I normally use. It also comes with a bolt lock.

I'm from New York originally but I moved down to Virginia where basically everything is legal. We shoot AUG's and G3's down here. Cigs are $4.95 a pack down here in America. You can literally go to a drive-thru liquor and fireworks store. Not kidding. A drive-thru, that sells LIQUOR and FIREWORKS at the same establishment. I bought this rifle so that I'd have something to take to New York when I come back for visits if I feel like doing some shooting, but I've moved on to bigger and badder guns now.

I'll be up in New York in mid May, so in case anybody wants to do face-to-face, then is the time to do it. If you want to do a face-to-face, you have to show me evidence that you passed a background check. I need to see a pistol permit and you need to sign a bill of sale. No deals in NYC or Yonkers. I'm pretty sure they have additional laws that I don't want to mess with.

postcontent:
Hard case, quad rail, red dot, bipod - LOADED!

This lightweight flat-top carbine (carbon) rifle is brand new, never fired - no rounds even chambered. 

It's loaded with extras - 45 degree forged iron sights, aluminum quad rail, a folding bipod, red dot optics, a Plano hard shell case and more. New rifle, new accessories. Comes with the manual and the Bushmaster aluminum 30-round "high capacity" magazine, too.

I bought it right around a month ago for quite a bit of money...

It's definitely one of the most bada*s AR-15s I've seen. 

New RI gun laws are going to make these things impossible to buy as soon as July of this year. Those of us lucky to have gotten one before that time get to keep it.

I got this for my now-ex. Fortunately she never got to use it. I have quite a bit of money into this (almost two grand). I need the money at this point.

It's a lightweight carbine, at just about 6 pounds. Leaves lots of room to add (more?) stuff on, and not end up with a 10+ pound rifle...

I posted a picture of this rifle setup to AR-15 Gun Owners Of America mentioning that I had it for sale, and the thread BLEW UP. The page admins reposted it. About a dozen other people reposted it to their own pages. All sorts of people wanted to buy it. It's a nationwide site though, and I'm not shipping it anywhere. RI only.

I would keep it, but I already have my own AR-15, and I don't need two. I need the money!

This sale is to be made in accordance with all applicable local, state, and federal laws.

The transfer can be done free of charge through an FFL that I deal with here in the Providence area.

No trades. NO TRADES!!! I will not deliver the rifle. Cash only. No checks, no money orders, no payment plans, etc. Too much risk involved. An honest person will understand this.

I'd like to make this a nice smooth transaction. As little aggravation as possible.

I am home during the day most days. Email me and I will get back to you very quickly.

First come first serve. You are responsible for knowing your own local laws and abide by them. No sales to anyone unable to legally purchase it. No kids, no criminals... you know the laws. We're sticking to them.

Get in touch.
